makedepends is/should be a restricted use array with as few/minimal assumptions as possible



Any packages that are HEAVILY suggested by the maintainer, but not absolutely... 100% required in order for it to be...
POSSIBLE for the package to compile

Each of these should also go in the optdepends, not makedepends

Example:systemd by default depends on dbus, but instead, one might use dbus-broker, or no dbus at all given that systemd has a private socket with sd_bus

Curl typically depends on openssl, but it actually just depends on "an ssl implementation".
users may prefer gnutls, wolfssl, libressl, or other

This is something that is especially important in traditional "core packages", the most important system components...
things like -
ssl: listed above
compiler/build tool: gcc,clang,meson,llvm

Display protocol/server: x11, wayland
The choice of a wayland compositor or xserver 

The graphics libraries, opencl, opengl, etc...

If your package is not a multicast dns tool that uses avahi libs - then avahi is not a dependency
No matter HOW MUCH you "THINK" that a user should have it installed
in which case it does NOT go in depends, or makedepends.
It goes in optdepends and suggested_packages

list goes on and on, basically do not depend on something, just because you depend on one of its transitive dependencies
